---
import ActBreak from '../ActBreak.astro';
import FigurePlate from '../FigurePlate.astro';
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act III"
  title="The Machine That Ran the Science"
  tease="A lab that pre-registers its bets, argues with itself, and can't declare victory by accident."
  id="act-3"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="architecture">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">05</span> The system</div>
    <h2>Three tiers, one loop</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      The doctrine became software in three tiers. At the bottom, the <strong>plant</strong>: a
      frozen language model (no weights are ever updated, anywhere in this project) with the
      lens-based writer and reader attached. In the middle, the doctrine as a
      <strong>controller</strong>: the entropy timing gate, the readback verifier, the budget
      monitor. And on top — the unusual part — an <strong>automated research loop</strong> that
      chose which experiment to run next.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_architecture"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 2"
      alt="Three-tier system diagram: frozen plant with actuator pair, doctrine controller, and auto-research loop"
      caption="The full stack. Lower tier: frozen plant + transported writes (h ← h + αJᵀu) and band-targeted readback. Middle: the doctrine as controller. Upper: the expected-free-energy selector, dual-closure gates, and adversarial review that ran the programme."
      gates={["gates/*.json", "efe_ledger.jsonl"]}
    />

    <p>
      Every experiment was <strong>pre-registered</strong> — seeds, commands, and pass criteria
      committed <em>before</em> dispatch. Every result became a <strong>gate record</strong>: a
      JSON file in the public repo binding claim to evidence. And closing a research loop required
      <strong>two gates at once</strong> — a code gate (tests pass) <em>and</em> a domain gate (the
      registered scientific criterion is met). Passing tests alone never closed anything.
    </p>

    <div class="stat-strip">
      <div class="card"><div class="stat-big">130</div><div class="stat-label">gate records committed</div></div>
      <div class="card"><div class="stat-big">27</div><div class="stat-label">selector cycles (EFE-chosen experiments)</div></div>
      <div class="card"><div class="stat-big">18</div><div class="stat-label">isolated adversarial reviews</div></div>
      <div class="card"><div class="stat-big">8</div><div class="stat-label">frozen checkpoints, 5 model families</div></div>
    </div>

    <details class="expand">
      <summary>Who chose the experiments? An expected-free-energy selector</summary>
      <div class="expand-body">
        <p>
          Experiment selection was delegated to an <strong>expected-free-energy (EFE) selector</strong>
          operating over registered menus — the same explore/exploit calculus active-inference agents
          use, here choosing which loop to fund next. Its ledger is public: 267 observation events,
          41 proposals, 27 spend entries, 9 menus. Eighteen <strong>adversarial reviews</strong> —
          agents briefed only on the gate records and contracts, never on the narrative — forced
          documented corrections along the way (including downgrading a readback claim from
          <em>confirm</em> to <em>screen</em>, review #12).
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="compute">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">06</span> The bill</div>
    <h2>Eighteen GPU-hours</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      Here's a number worth sitting with: the entire registered programme through L20 — every
      replication, every seed, every negative result — cost <strong>18.17 GPU-hours</strong> on a
      single shared node. Not a datacenter. One machine, three weekends' worth of compute, and a
      discipline that wasted none of it.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_compute"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 3"
      alt="Per-loop GPU-hours as bars with a cumulative total line reaching about 19 hours including L22"
      caption="The compute ledger, loop by loop. Bars: per-loop GPU-hours; line: cumulative total (18.17 h through the 19 budgeted loops; 19.02 h including the later L22 benchmark). The single largest item is the 27B loadability replication (L1b, 6.1 h)."
      gates={["research/state.json"]}
    />

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="callout-title">Why so cheap?</div>
      <p>
        Because the EFE selector treats compute like a portfolio: each candidate experiment is
        scored by what it would <em>teach</em> against what it would <em>cost</em>, and the
        pre-registration discipline means no experiment is ever re-run to fish for a better answer.
        Frugality here isn't a constraint — it's a consequence of the method.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
